# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: act-of-consolidation-1854
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The **Act of Consolidation**, more formally known as the **act of February 2, 1854** (P.L.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] 16), is legislation of the Pennsylvania General Assembly that created the consolidated City and County of Philadelphia, expanding the city's territory to the entirety of Philadelphia County and dissolving the other municipal authorities in the county.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The law was enacted by the General Assembly and approved February 2, 1854, by Governor William Bigler.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] This act consolidated all remaining townships, districts, and boroughs within the County of Philadelphia, dissolving their governmental structures and bringing all municipal authority within the county under the auspices of the Philadelphia government.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Additionally, any unincorporated areas were included in the consolidation.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The consolidation was drafted to help combat lawlessness that the many local governments could not handle separately and to bring in much-needed tax revenue for the State.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] In early 1854, the city of Philadelphia's boundaries extended east and west between the Delaware and Schuylkill Rivers and north and south between Vine and South streets, representing the present-day Center City section of Philadelphia.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The rest of Philadelphia County contained thirteen townships, six boroughs and nine districts.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Philadelphia City's recent influx of immigrants spilled over into the rest of Philadelphia County, surging the area's population.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] In 1840, Philadelphia's population was 93,665 and the rest of the county was 164,372; by 1850 the populations were 121,376 and 287,385 respectively.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] One of the major reasons put forth for the consolidation of the city was the county's inability to govern.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Law enforcement found it difficult to enforce the peace.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] A person could break the law in Philadelphia City and quickly cross the border and escape punishment.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Districts outside Philadelphia could not control their criminal elements and at the same time refused to let Philadelphia get involved.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] An example of how poorly law enforcement agencies worked together was in May, 1844 when an anti-Catholic riot erupted in Kensington.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The sheriff was the only police officer available in Kensington at the time and when Philadelphia's militia was called they hesitated because they hadn't been reimbursed for past calls.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] By the time the militia arrived, the riot was out of control.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Attempts to improve the issue included an 1845 law that required several of the surrounding districts to maintain adequate law enforcement and an 1850 act that gave Philadelphia law enforcement the authority to police seven surrounding districts.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] As a result, the act also achieved one of its intended roles: Expand and strengthen the jurisdiction of the Philadelphia Police Department.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The other major reason for consolidation was that Philadelphia's actual population center was not in Philadelphia, but north of Vine Street.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Between 1844 and 1854, Philadelphia's population grew by 29.5 percent.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Places like Spring Garden grew by 111.5 percent, and the Kensington section of Philadelphia grew by 109.5 percent.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] This population shift was draining the city of much-needed tax revenue for police and fire departments, water, sewage, and other city improvements.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] There had been several unsuccessful proposals at consolidation before 1854.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The main opposition of consolidation came from the Whig Party.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The Whigs usually dominated Philadelphia City elections while the outlying districts were dominated by the Democrats and the Whigs feared they would lose power within the city.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] With support from all the city's major newspapers, and the end of the Whig party's existence around that time, the consolidation overcame opposition and the issue was brought to the Pennsylvania General Assembly.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Eli Kirk Price brought the issue to the Pennsylvania Senate while Matthias W.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Patterson brought it to the House of Representatives.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] A bill was produced on December 20, 1853, and by January 31, 1854, the bill had passed both houses.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The bill was then brought to Governor William Bigler, who was in Erie, Pennsylvania.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Bigler was awoken out of bed before midnight on February 2 and signed the bill into law.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The signing was rushed because several districts were considering assuming new debts for railroad loans and other projects, with the expectation that the consolidated city would pay instead.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The Act of Consolidation, along with creating Philadelphia's modern border, gave executive power to a mayor who would be elected every two years.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The mayor was given substantial control of the police department and control of municipal administration and executive departments with oversight and control of the budget from the city council.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] On March 11 there was a large celebration for the consolidation.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Governor Bigler, members of the legislature, and chief officers of the state visited the city for the celebration.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Events included an excursion on the Delaware River, a ball at the Philadelphia Chinese Museum and a banquet at the Sansom Street Hall the next day.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Although the city and county now shared the same boundaries, a number of city and county functions remained separate.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Many of these functions were overseen by "City Commissioners" who were elected separately from the city council and mayor.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] In 1951, the state constitution was amended to allow cities and counties to fully merge, and Philadelphia voters adopted a new home rule charter that merged nearly all city and county institutions.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The new charter took effect in January 1952.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Although Philadelphia County has effectively been a legal nullity since then, the county row offices still exist, though all except the Register of Wills are subject to city civil service rules.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] Ongoing measures consolidated authority, advancing administrative transitions, sustaining effective, viable executive norms.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/act-of-consolidation-1854] The following is a list of municipal authorities which were consolidated into the modern City and County of Philadelphia.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/aramingo-borough-pennsylvania] Aramingo Borough was created out of the Northern Liberties Township and was incorporated on April 11, 1850.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/aramingo-borough-pennsylvania] The name is an abbreviation and alteration from the Native American name of the stream adjacent, called by the Swedes and English, Gunner’s Run.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/aramingo-borough-pennsylvania] The original name was Tumanaraming, meaning "Wolf Walk." By cutting off the first five letters and adding an o at the end, the word "Aramingo" was coined.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/aramingo-borough-pennsylvania] Aramingo Avenue remains a major road in Port Richmond, Fishtown, and other neighborhoods in near Northeast Philadelphia.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/aramingo-borough-pennsylvania] It is home to many stores and shopping plazas.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] The name *Belmont* is still used as a neighborhood name for the area, although it no longer refers to any legal entity.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] Similar name-inheritance (where the name of a former municipality lives on as a neighborhood name without formal definition) is seen in other Philadelphia neighborhoods.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] Belmont District was created by act of the Assembly on April 14, 1853.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] It embraced the part of Blockley Township which lay along the Schuylkill River from the northern boundary-line of West Philadelphia to the northern boundary-line between Philadelphia and Montgomery counties, and had also its western boundary on that line.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] This district had scarcely time to be organized before the Act of Consolidation of February 2, 1854, put an end to its franchises.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] The name was derived from Belmont, the country seat of the Peters family, which is now part of Fairmount Park.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] The mansion was erected by William Peters about 1743, and the name was descriptive of the fine position of the property and suggestive of the beautiful views of the river and valley of the Schuylkill.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] The property became the estate of Judge Richard Peters, Jr., of the United States District Court; he lived there until his death, August 22, 1828.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/belmont-district-pennsylvania] The Belmont School was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1988.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] Within its boundaries were the villages of Hamilton, Mantua, West Philadelphia, Hestonville and Haddington.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] It was traversed by the Darby Road (today's Woodland Avenue) and Chadd’s Ford or Baltimore Pike, the road to West Chester, to Haverford and to Lancaster.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] The name is derived from Blockley, a parish in England in Worcestershire (since 1931 in Gloucestershire) from which the township's founder, William Warner, hailed.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] In Philadelphia, "Blockley" was synonymous with the Blockley Almshouse that opened here in 1832.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] The township also contained **The Woodlands**; the former estate of William Hamilton, grandson of Andrew Hamilton, which was converted in 1840 to the Woodlands Cemetery.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] The boundaries and area changed on February 17, 1844, when the area encompassing Mantua and Hamilton were incorporated into the Borough of West Philadelphia, dividing the remaining township into two almost unconnected sections.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/blockley-township-pennsylvania] The township was incorporated into Philadelphia proper by the 1854 Act of Consolidation.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] In the United States Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, a **borough** (sometimes spelled **boro**) is a self-governing municipal entity, equivalent to a town in most jurisdictions, usually smaller than a city, but with a similar population density in its residential areas.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] Sometimes thought of as "junior cities", boroughs generally have fewer powers and responsibilities than full-fledged cities.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] All municipalities in Pennsylvania are classified as either cities, boroughs, or townships.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] The only exception is the town of Bloomsburg, recognized by the state government as the only incorporated town in Pennsylvania.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] Compared to townships, boroughs tend to have more developed business districts and concentrations of public and commercial office buildings, including courthouses.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] Boroughs have larger populations, smaller aerial footprints, and more concentrated development than the average townships, with many boroughs being surrounded by a township of a related or even the same name.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] There are 956 boroughs and 56 cities in Pennsylvania.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/borough-pennsylvania] Many home rule municipalities remain classified as boroughs or townships for certain purposes, even if the state's borough and township codes no longer apply to them.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The historic boundaries of the former borough of Bridesburg were the original course of Frankford Creek around the south and west, the Delaware River to the southeast, and Port Richmond to the southwest, along a border at Pike Street near Wheatsheaf Lane.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Aramingo Avenue/I-95 is the border to the western edge of the neighborhood that borders Frankford.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Adjacent neighborhoods are Wissinoming to the northeast, Whitehall to the north, Frankford to the northwest, and Port Richmond to the southwest.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The 19137 ZIP Code, of which Bridesburg forms the major part, extends as far to the southwest as Castor Avenue, and includes some area to the northwest of I-95 and the original course of Frankford Creek.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] A small portion of Bridesburg (also 19137) is situated directly next to the 19124 ZIP code known as Frankford.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Physical boundaries of Bridesburg are: Bridge Street on the north, Aramingo Avenue and I-95 to the northwest, Frankford Creek to the south, and the Delaware River to the east.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Before the arrival of Europeans, the Lenni Lenape Indians inhabited the region.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Explorer Henry Hudson in 1609 was the first European to set foot in this region, and based on his findings these Indians were considered to be the first inhabitants of the area.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] In 1638, the Swedes bought land east of the Delaware River from the Indians and named it New Sweden.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The Swedes lived with the Indians on friendly terms.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] By 1645 the Swedes had expanded to the Northeast of modern-day Philadelphia, and in 1647 the Dutch arrived.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] But it was not until the 1680s when the English came with William Penn that the area was actually developed.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] After 1750, Germans then settled the area, particularly in Bridesburg and Frankford.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] On April 1, 1833, Philadelphia County bought the Kirkbride bridge and two-and-a-half acres of land annexed for $5,500.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Kirkbridesburg was considered too long a name for convenience, and the shorter "Bridesburg" was adopted.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Bridesburg was incorporated as a borough on April 1, 1848.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] In 1854, the borough was annexed to the city of Philadelphia in the Act of Consolidation.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The region was known in Colonial times as Point-no-Point, due to the deceptive appearance of the blunt cape at the mouth of Frankford Creek.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] When first seen going northward it appeared to be a point, sharply jutting into the stream, but upon approaching, it lost its character and seemed to be an ordinary portion of the right bank; on further approach it seemed to again jut out into a point.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Many famous personalities in history have passed through the lands of Point-no-Point.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The second President of the United States wrote a letter to his wife Abigail describing his travels in Point-no-Point.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Bridesburg was incorporated as a borough on April 1, 1848; it included the peninsula between the lower Frankford Creek and the Delaware River, and beyond Richmond district, the boundary lying near the projected line of Pike street, not far from Wheat Sheaf Lane.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] It was first called Kirkbridesburg, for Joseph Kirkbride, who operated a ferry to New Jersey, and in 1811 built a toll bridge at Bridge street over Frankford Creek.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The villagers decided the name was too long, and shortened it to Bridesburg.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The Bridesburg Manufacturing Company was established in 1820 by Kirkbride.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] It was originally a textile mill on Frankford Creek.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Industry followed the company into Bridesburg, especially with the establishment of the Bridesburg Manufacturing Company and the U.S.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] At the end of the 19th century, Costello, Cooey & Co., a company specializing in kidskin leather (from young goats) and the chromium tanning process, employed more than 100 workers.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Robert Cooey (1840-1903), an emigrant from Newtownstewart, County Tyrone, arrived in Philadelphia on the packet ship *The Provincialist* in 1851 with his sister Isabella at the age of 10.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] He went to work with his brother and father in the tanneries of the Northern Liberties.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] In 1877, he partnered. partnered with Mark Costello (1844-1928), an emigrant from Ballinderry, to form a Philadelphia tannery, with Charles O'Neill, John McStay, and Christopher Conway.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] They rented a narrow store front at 2nd & Willow Street, with its rail lines down the center, bringing livestock and their valuable skin, especially goats, sheep and calves but also cattle and horses.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The firm specialized in moroccan leather and worked leather into products ranging from gloves to handbags to shoes.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] In 1895, John Rose & Sons, undertakers, John Rose (1855-1916), an emigrant cabinetmaker from London, proprietor, opened at 2616 Bridge Street, in a former tavern and schoolhouse that still stands today, with son Alfred P.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The family served the community as the Rose Funeral Home until 2023.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] William Tippetts Rose, a son, ran parlors in Frankford, and purchased the Beach Haven Terrace Yacht Club on Long Beach Island in 1933.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Another son Charles Samuel Rose married Martha Cooey, the daughter of Robert Cooey and Sophia Borbeck, at the Bridesburg Presbyterian Church, on January 27, 1909.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Their sons Robert Cooey Rose and John Samuel Rose operated funeral businesses Frankford and Lawncrest into the 1970s.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Martha, her children, grandchildren and descendants continue the family tradition of life on Long Beach Island.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Bridesburg Foundry has been in continuous operation since 1914.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The company began in Bridesburg and then moved to its present location in Whitehall, Pennsylvania in 1941.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Polish families migrated to Bridesburg between 1900 and 1920.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] "The Frankford leather plant of Robert H.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Foerderer Inc. originally hired Polish men to work in curing the hides.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] This process consisted of soaking hides for days in dog manure to soften it.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The smell of the manure and the need to handle the soaked leather made this job unacceptable to most Philadelphia workers.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Bridesburg is home to the second oldest VFW Post in the world, founded in 1899.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Bridesburg is also home to the Joseph A.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The Ferko String Band is a member of the Philadelphia String Band Association, which is a division of the Philadelphia Mummers Parade.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] As of the 2010 Census, Bridesburg had a population of 8,638, of which 90% was white, 5.5% Hispanic, 1.9% was black or African-American, 0.6% was Asian, and the remaining 2% was other or mixed races.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The School District of Philadelphia operates Bridesburg Elementary School, which serves elementary school students.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Harding Middle School and Frankford High School.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] At one time, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia operated two Catholic schools in Bridesburg: All Saints School (1864-2004) and St.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Pope John Paul II Regional Catholic School (formerly St.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] John Cantius Elementary School) was in operation from 2004 until 2012.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Students choosing Catholic education in a Catholic school attend Blessed Trinity Regional School (formerly St.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Timothy's School) in Mayfair since September 2012.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The United States Post Office operates the Bridesburg Post Office at 2734 Orthodox Street.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] SEPTA bus routes 25, 73, 41, and 84 all run in/near the neighborhood.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bridesburg-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Bridesburg station of the Trenton Line of SEPTA Regional Rail is located in the neighborhood.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bristol-township-philadelphia-county-pennsylvania] Bristol Township was located at the north end of Philadelphia County, at the intersection of the angle which runs down from the extreme point between Philadelphia and Montgomery counties.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bristol-township-philadelphia-county-pennsylvania] It was of irregular form, and was bounded on the northwest by a portion of Springfield Township, Montgomery County; on the northeast by Cheltenham Township, Montgomery County.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bristol-township-philadelphia-county-pennsylvania] It extended along the latter to Oxford Township, but was bounded mainly on the east by Tacony Creek, on the south partly by the Wingohocking and the Northern Liberties Township, and on the west and southwest by Germantown Borough and Germantown Township.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bristol-township-philadelphia-county-pennsylvania] The Old York Road ran through it to Branchtown and Milestown (now East Oak Lane), and thence to Bucks County.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bristol-township-philadelphia-county-pennsylvania] Greatest length, five and one-half miles; greatest breadth, three miles; area, 5,650 acres (23 km2).
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/bristol-township-philadelphia-county-pennsylvania] The name is derived from the city of Bristol in England.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Byberry had a strong abolitionist presence and may have been an original stop on the Underground Railroad.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Today, the area occupied by the township is mostly synonymous with the neighborhood of Somerton, as the neighborhoods of Byberry and Somerton tend to overlap.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] A township in the extreme northeastern part of the County of Philadelphia; bounded on the east and northeast by Poquessing Creek and Bucks County; on the northwest by Montgomery County; and on the west and southwest by the Township of Moreland.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Its greatest length was estimated at 5 miles (8.0 kilometres); its greatest breadth, 2+1⁄2 miles (4.0 kilometres); area, 4.700 acres (0.01902 km2).
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The area was originally settled in the mid-17th century by Swedes.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] In 1675, four young, single brothers, Nathaniel, Thomas, Daniel and William Walton, arrived at Newcastle from England and, having first prospected the land in the neighborhood of the Delaware River, chose this area along the Poquessing Creek to settle.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] They gave it the name Byberry, in honor of their native town, near Bristol, in England.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] They were joined after the arrival of the ship Welcome in 1682, by Giles and Joseph Knight, John Carver, John Hart, Richard Collett and their families, and others.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Byberry was the birthplace of Benjamin Rush, a signer of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] The township was consolidated and established soon after the arrival of William Penn.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Byberry Township initially consisted only of a few villages, and was the most rural of all the townships of Philadelphia County.
[src:act-of-consolidation-1854/byberry-philadelphia-pennsylvania] Byberry Crossroads, once called Plumbsock, and Knightsville were the principal villages.
